"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822851","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-23","<p>The answer we provided for PQ 120661 still stands: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-12-20/120661/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-12-20/120661/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice Court Proceedings Database holds information on defendants proceeded against, found guilty and sentenced for criminal offences in England and Wales. This centrally held information does not include all the specific circumstances of each case, such as a defendant’s nationality. To collect and collate the information required would therefore incur a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-01-23T17:23:23.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822851/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822851/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-15","Community Orders: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 8 January 2018 to Question 120661, on Community Orders: Females, how many women received a community sentence by status of (a) foreign national and (b) British national in each of the last five whole reporting years; and what the offence category for each of those nationalities was in that time period.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","122534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822852","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-18","<p>The Treasury does not make assessments of bank branch closures. The decision to close a branch remains a commercial judgement for banks. However, the impact on communities must be understood, considered and mitigated where possible.</p><p> </p><p>The industry’s Access to Banking Standard, launched in May 2017, commits banks to ensure personal and business customers are better informed about branch closures and the reasons for them closing, along with the options they have locally to continue to access banking services, including specialist assistance for customers who need more help. The Access to Banking Standard is monitored and enforced by the independent Lending Standards Board.</p><p> </p><p>99% of banks’ personal and 95% of banks’ business customers are now able to withdraw cash, deposit cash and cheques, and make balance enquiries at a Post Office counter via its network of 11,600 branches. At Autumn Budget 2017, my predecessor wrote to the Post Office and UK Finance to ask them to raise public awareness of the banking services available at the Post Office for individuals and SMEs. I look forward to receiving their proposals later this month.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-01-18T17:33:46.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822852/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822852/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-15","Royal Bank of Scotland: Midlothian","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will make an assessment of the implications for local communities of the closure of RBS branches in (a) Penicuik and (b) Bonnyrigg later this year; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Danielle Rowley","Midlothian","Danielle Rowley","122535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822853","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-18","<p>The government is committed to building an economy that works for everyone and supporting people with protected characteristics. For example, we have increased the personal allowance and the National Living Wage; by 2018-19, over 700,000 women will be taken out of income tax altogether, and over 60% of those currently benefitting from the National Living Wage are women. The proportion of women in work is at a joint record high, and the gender pay gap for full-time employees is at a record low. The government is also spending over £50bn per year on benefits to support disabled people and people with health conditions.</p><p> </p><p>In line with the Government’s legal responsibilities and policy commitment to promote fairness, the Treasury and other Government departments fully comply with the Public Sector Equality Duty, including with respect to all publication requirements.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-01-18T13:39:05.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822853/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822853/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-15","Autumn Budget 2017","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made about the financial effect of Autumn Budget 2017 on (a) women and (b) people with protected characteristics.","false","Biography information for Danielle Rowley","Midlothian","Danielle Rowley","122536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822854","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-22","<p>No one should ever have to sleep rough. That is why Government has committed to halving rough sleeping by 2022 and eliminating it altogether by 2027. We have announced a new Rough Sleeping and Homelessness Reduction Taskforce, chaired by the Housing Secretary, which will drive forward the implementation of a cross-Government strategy to tackle this issue.</p><p>We have allocated over £1 billion through to 2020, following the 2015 Spending Review, to prevent and reduce all forms of homelessness. This includes £28 million announced at Budget to pilot a Housing First approach for some of the rough sleepers with the most complex needs.</p><p>Local authorities should work together with partners to provide basic emergency accommodation to minimise the risk of harm to individuals when the temperature drops.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","122538","2018-01-22T17:02:10.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822854/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822854/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-15","Sleeping Rough: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to change its guidance on the Severe Weather Emergency Protocol and extended weather provision; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","122537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822855","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-22","<p>No one should ever have to sleep rough. That is why Government has committed to halving rough sleeping by 2022 and eliminating it altogether by 2027. We have announced a new Rough Sleeping and Homelessness Reduction Taskforce, chaired by the Housing Secretary, which will drive forward the implementation of a cross-Government strategy to tackle this issue.</p><p>We have allocated over £1 billion through to 2020, following the 2015 Spending Review, to prevent and reduce all forms of homelessness. This includes £28 million announced at Budget to pilot a Housing First approach for some of the rough sleepers with the most complex needs.</p><p>Local authorities should work together with partners to provide basic emergency accommodation to minimise the risk of harm to individuals when the temperature drops.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","122537","2018-01-22T17:02:10.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822855/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822855/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-15","Sleeping Rough: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to change legal protections for people sleeping rough in England during severe weather; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","122538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822856","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-22","<p>The then Minister for Small Business, Consumers and Corporate Responsibility hosted the EU Exit Consumer Roundtable on 2 November 2017. A Minister from the Department for Exiting the European Union also attended. It was attended by representatives from Which?, MoneySavingExpert , Citizens Advice, Citizens Advice Scotland, the Consumer Council of Northern Ireland and the Chartered Trading Standards Institute.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-22T11:37:44.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822856/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822856/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-15","Consumers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2017 to Question 106304, whether his Department has set a date for the roundtable event with consumer groups to discuss negotiations on the UK leaving the EU and their implications for consumers in the UK.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","122539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822857","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-19","<p>HMRC publish the estimated costs of principal tax reliefs: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579720/Dec_16_Main_Reliefs_Final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579720/Dec_16_Main_Reliefs_Final.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The estimated cost of the personal savings allowance in 2016-17 is £370m. The next version of this publication covering 2017-18 will be published later in the year.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-01-19T13:54:14.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822857/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822857/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-15","Personal Savings: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the amount lost to the public purse as a result of the Personal Savings Allowance in (a) 2016-17 and (b) 2017-18 to date.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","122540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822858","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-22","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency’s (DVSA) testing facility at Shrewsbury is not currently available for disposal. Although the site has been identified as being surplus to DVSA’s future requirements, DVSA is in the process of securing an alternative service delivery model for those services that are delivered from the site.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-01-22T12:28:10.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822858/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822858/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-15","Valuation Office Agency: Shrewsbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress is being made on the sale of the Valuation Office Agency testing facility in Shrewsbury.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","122541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822859","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-23","<p>This data is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>National Health Service organisations are responsible locally for their own policy on internal travel arrangements and car parking, taking into account operational circumstances and community interests.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS patient, visitor and staff car parking principles (first published in August 2014 and then updated in October 2015), set out a nationally consistent approach to determining car parking policies, making clear the rules which NHS trusts should follow when making decisions about car parking. However, the provision of parking spaces for patients, staff, contractors, and other visitors to the site and the level of any charges that are made to use them are matters for individual NHS trusts.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","122543 ; 122544 ; 122545 ; 122546","2018-01-23T14:45:09.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822859/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/822859/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-15","Hospitals: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many hospital trusts in England have considered installing a pay on exit or similar scheme since the publication of his Department's guidance on NHS patient, visitor and staff car parking principles, last updated on 29 October 2015; and how many hospital trusts (a) are planning to install such a scheme in 2018 and (b) have decided against installing such a scheme.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","122542"
