"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821534","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-22","<p>My Department and the Department of Health and Social Care are in regular contact about public health policy and funding, including in relation to Public Health Grant.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-01-22T17:05:55.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821534/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821534/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-12","Public Health: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent discussions he has had with the Health Secretary on the effect of changes in public health grants on council budgets.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","122452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821535","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-22","<p>On 21 December 2017 the Government published its response to the consultation on ‘ Tackling unfair practices in the leasehold market’. This set out a range of measures to cut out unfair and abusive practices within the leasehold system, including introducing legislation to prohibit the development of new build leasehold houses, other than in exceptional circumstances; and restricting ground rents in newly established leases of houses and flats to a peppercorn (zero financial value).</p><p>For existing leaseholders, the Government wants to see developer compensation schemes going further and faster, with support extended to all those with onerous ground rents, including second hand buyers and for customers to be proactively contacted. We will be keeping a close eye on progress and will consider measures that could be pursued to take action if necessary. We have also set out work with the Law Commission to make buying a freehold or extending a lease easier, faster, fairer and cheaper.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","122448 ; 122451","2018-01-22T17:57:48.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821535/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821535/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-12","Leasehold: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what plans his Department has to cap rises in leasehold payments for homeowners.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","122453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821536","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-22","<p>An independent evaluation of GP at Hand is being commissioned by Hammersmith and Fulham Clinical Commissioning Group and the scope and specification for this are currently in development.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-22T11:47:10.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821536/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821536/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-12","GP at Hand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 13 December 2017 to Question 117917, when his Department plans to publish the first evaluation of the effect of the GP at Hand service.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","122454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821537","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-25","<p>Officials from my Department attend a monthly meeting hosted by both Public Health England (PHE) and the Department of Health and Social Care (DHSC) which specifically focuses on matters relating to the Public Health Grant. In addition to such meetings, officials from my Department have frequent ad-hoc dialogue on the Public Health Grant with their counterparts from PHE and DHSC.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-01-25T16:36:40.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821537/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821537/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-12","Public Health: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what meetings (a) Ministers in his Department and (b) officials in his Department have had with Public Health England on the public health grant in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","122455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821538","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-18","<p>Officials are currently working with the outsourced catering supplier to remove plastic bottles from sale in the Defra restaurants.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-18T16:24:29.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821538/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821538/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821538/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-12","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department plans to stop the sale of drinks in disposable plastic bottles in its offices.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","122456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821539","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-22","<p>The government does not prescribe centrally where local government pension funds should invest their assets. Funds are responsible and accountable for their own decisions, provided that they act reasonably and follow the Local Government Pension Scheme Investment Regulations 2016 and associated guidance. <br> <br> Local government pension funds should make the pursuit of a financial return their predominant concern but they may also take into account purely non-financial considerations provided that doing so would not involve a significant risk of financial detriment and they have good reason to believe that scheme members would support their decision. <br> <br> Funds are required to set out their policy on how environmental, social or corporate governance concerns are taken into account in their Investment Strategy Statement. The Regulations also require this statement to be published and kept under review.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-01-22T16:55:52.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821539/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821539/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821539/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-12","Local Government: Pension Funds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on local government pension funds being used to invest in fossil fuels; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","122457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821540","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>Local authorities may incur more expenditure than they have budgeted for a range of reasons, including increases in demand for services and unforeseeable events. This is why every local authority is required to maintain a level of unallocated reserve commensurate with sound financial risk management.</p><p>The Department collects and publishes individual local authority expenditure data for both budget and outturn, and these are available at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</a>.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-01-23T14:04:46.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821540/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821540/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-12","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) county and (b) district councils which have overspent on their budgets in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","122458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821541","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-19","<p>The Department uses both external assurance and internal governance procedures to assess its ability to deliver its functions.</p><p>Externally, the National Audit Office (NAO) carries out value for money studies of the Department’s work areas and to recommend how to improve value for money and delivery of services. These reports are followed up by the Public Accounts Committee, which makes recommendations to the Department.</p><p>Internally, high-level governance is provided by the Departmental Board, the Audit and Risk Assurance Committee and the Executive Team; the Executive Team also ensures that delivery performance is monitored effectively by Director General-led Portfolio Boards. The Department’s Annual Report and Accounts includes performance monitoring, financial monitoring, and audit, as well as setting out how the Department ensures it can deliver its functions. This includes describing how Departmental capability is assured, for example, through the Department’s People Plan, as well as examining risks to the Department and to delivery of its objectives, and assurance and accountability of local government, the Local Growth Fund, and the Department’s arms’ length bodies.</p><p>Additionally, the Department is currently planning to ensure it can deliver its functions in the future. The work on the Single Departmental Plan sets out what the Department will achieve over the next five years and how we measure success. Our Business Planning work will ensure that the Department has the tools to deliver these objectives.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-01-19T13:38:08.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821541/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821541/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821541/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-12","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when his Department's ability to deliver its functions was last assessed.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","122459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821542","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-22","<p>This is a matter for the Department of Health and Social Care.</p><p>This Department does not hold information on the data requested.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-01-22T17:48:00.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821542/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821542/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-12","Abuse: Vulnerable Adults","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many adult abuse concerns were reported to local authorities in each of the last 12 months; and how many of those cases were escalated to become safeguarding issues.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","122460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821543","Department for Education","false","2018-01-22","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. However, published data on referrals is distributed annually in the statistical first release ‘Characteristics of children in need’, which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/characteristics-of-children-in-need-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/characteristics-of-children-in-need-2016-to-2017</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-22T17:47:36.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821543/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821543/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-12","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education,  how many incidents of alleged child abuse were reported to local authorities in each of the last 12 months; and how many of those reports were escalated to become safeguarding issues.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","122461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821544","Department for Education","false","2018-01-17","<p>The data requested is published in table 6 of the additional tables by pupil characteristics within the ‘Early years foundation stage profile results: 2016 to 2017’ statistical first release available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/early-years-foundation-stage-profile-results-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/early-years-foundation-stage-profile-results-2016-to-2017</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-17T17:23:28.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821544/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821544/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821544/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-12","Pre-school Education: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what percentage of children in (a) Nottinghamshire and (b) England who are (i) eligible and (ii) not eligible for free school meals have achieved school readiness standards at the end of the Early Years Foundation Stage in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","122462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821545","Department for Education","false","2018-01-17","<p>Ofsted inspection data shows that in Nottinghamshire, 15% of pupils were in outstanding primary schools and 76% in good primary schools as at August 31, 2017. In England, 20% of pupils were in outstanding primary schools and 70% in good primary schools as at August 31, 2017.</p><p>Ofsted inspection data also shows that in Nottinghamshire, 30% of pupils were in outstanding secondary schools and 60% in good secondary schools as at August 31, 2017. In England, 28% of pupils were in outstanding secondary schools and 55% in good secondary schools as at August 31, 2017.</p><p>Ofsted’s latest statistics are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/maintained-schools-and-academies-inspections-and-outcomes-as-at-31-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/maintained-schools-and-academies-inspections-and-outcomes-as-at-31-august-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-17T17:45:09.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821545/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821545/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821545/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-12","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the proportion of (a) primary and (b) secondary age children in (i) Nottinghamshire and (ii) England that attend a school rated (A) outstanding and (B) good by Ofsted.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","122463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821546","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-17","<p>DCMS commissions independent evaluations of the National Citizen Service to assess the impact and value for money of the NCS programme.</p><p> </p><p>The youth sector evidence base is not yet sufficiently developed to enable robust comparison between different programmes. DCMS is supporting youth organisations to develop the sector evidence base such as through funding for the Centre for Youth Impact and the £1m made available to evaluate the Youth Investment Fund.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","122466","2018-01-17T10:43:58.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821546/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821546/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821546/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-12","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if he will widen the scope of the commissioned annual independent evaluation of the National Citizen Service (NCS) in order to make comparisons with other youth programmes with similar aims to NCS.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","122464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821547","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-17","<p>DCMS has not received any requests to use participant data held for evaluations of the NCS programme this data and has no plans to release the data at this time.</p><p> </p><p>Separately, we are working with the Centre for Youth Impact to consider what more could be done to strengthen the collective evidence base for youth provision.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-01-17T10:48:02.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821547/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821547/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-12","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if he will enable other youth programmes to make use of the control group of non-National Citizen Service (NCS) participants secured for the annual independent evaluation of the NCS programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","122465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821548","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-17","<p>DCMS commissions independent evaluations of the National Citizen Service to assess the impact and value for money of the NCS programme.</p><p> </p><p>The youth sector evidence base is not yet sufficiently developed to enable robust comparison between different programmes. DCMS is supporting youth organisations to develop the sector evidence base such as through funding for the Centre for Youth Impact and the £1m made available to evaluate the Youth Investment Fund.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","122464","2018-01-17T10:43:58.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821548/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821548/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-12","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the (a) effectiveness and (b) value for money of the National Citizen Service in comparison to other youth programmes with similar aims.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","122466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821549","Department for Education","false","2018-01-22","<p>Ofsted inspection data shows that in Nottinghamshire there were 5,682 pupils eligible for free school meals in primary schools. Of these pupils, 87% were in outstanding and good schools as at 31 August 2017. In England there were 500,386 pupils eligible for free school meals in primary schools of which 87% were in outstanding and good schools as at 31 August 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Ofsted inspection data also shows that in Nottinghamshire there were 3,995 pupils eligible for free school meals in secondary schools. Of these 89% were in outstanding and good schools as at 31 August 2017. In England there were 302,372 pupils eligible for free school meals in primary schools of which 75% were in outstanding and good schools as at 31 August 2017.</p><p> </p><p>See Ofsted’s latest data release at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/maintained-schools-and-academies-inspections-and-outcomes-as-at-31-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/maintained-schools-and-academies-inspections-and-outcomes-as-at-31-august-2017</a>.</p><p> </p><p>For Pupils Data:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-22T17:29:14.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821549/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821549/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-12","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of (a) primary school and (b) secondary school children who are eligible for free school meals in (i) Nottinghamshire and (ii) England attend a school rated good and outstanding by Ofsted.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","122467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821550","Department for Education","false","2018-01-17","<p>The number and proportion of pupils achieving the expected standard in a) reading, b) writing, c) maths and d) all three combined, split by free school meal eligibility, in 2017 for the requested constituencies can be found in the attached table.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-17T17:53:36.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821550/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821550/answer","122468 Table Attachment.docx","122468 Table Attachment.docx","122468 Table","122468 Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821550/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-12","Education: Nottinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children in (a) Ashfield, (b) Rushcliffe and (c) Mansfield who are (i) eligible and (ii) not eligible for free school meals reached the expected standard in (A) reading, (B) writing, (C) maths and (D) all of those subjects at the end of Key Stage 2 in 2017.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","122468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821551","Department for Education","false","2018-01-17","<p>Key stage 4 pupil attainment (including Attainment 8) in 2016/17, for England, split by eligibility for free school meals, will be published in the department’s statistical first release on 25 January 2018[1]. Parliamentary constituency data for all pupils will also be published on 25 January and breakdowns by pupil characteristics (such as eligibility for free school meals) will be available from that date.</p><p>The Average Attainment 8 score of pupils, at the end of key stage 4, split by eligibility for free school meals (FSM) in each requested constituency for 2015/16 is available in the attached table.</p><p>The 2015/16 figures for England are published in the ‘Characteristics national tables’ as part of the department’s statistical first release.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-gcses-key-stage-4" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-gcses-key-stage-4</a> - Select the ‘Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2016 to 2017’ link at the top of the page when it is added on 25 January and downloading the ‘characteristics national tables’ file.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-17T17:02:09.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821551/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821551/answer","122469 Table.docx","122469 Table.docx","122469 Table","122469 Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821551/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-12","GCSE: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average Attainment 8 score is per pupil who is (a) eligible and (b) not eligible for free school meals in (i) Ashfield, (ii) Mansfield, (iii) Rushcliffe and (iv) England in 2016 and 2017.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","122469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821552","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-22","<p>The Chancellor’s Department does not operate a fleet of cars.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury uses two cars provided by the Government Car Service, which will be included in the return from the Department for Transport.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-01-22T15:56:47.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821552/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/821552/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-12","Treasury: Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many vehicles in his Department's fleet are (a) electric vehicles and (b) ultra-low emission vehicles.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","122470"
